</i> ‘remedy’ + <i>hildr</i> ‘battle, war’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bottles","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bottle  ."]},{"name":"Boutell","meanings":["English (Essex and Suffolk): nickname perhaps for a flour sifter, from Anglo-Norman <i>boletel</i>, <i>buletel</i> ‘sieve, bolting-cloth’ (Old French <i>buletel</i>, earlier <i>buretel</i>) ‘sieve’. In Middle English <i>buletel</i> was used to denote a kind of cloth especially prepared for sifting, and the name may have been given to a maker of this cloth or be a shortened form of   Boulter  ."]},{"name":"Buttles","meanings":["English: probably a variant of <b>Buttle</b>, itself a variant of   Bottle   or   Boutell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Bottle was born in 1380, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary Ann Jackson. He died in 1427, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1380–1427":"1380–1427","1384–1429":"1384–1429","1414–1492":"1414–1492","1414":"1414","1384":"1384","1492":"1492","1380":"1380","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Finwick, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1427":"1380–1427","1384–1429":"1384–1429","1414–1492":"1414–1492","1414":"1414","1384":"1384","14